<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06143177 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06143177 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  MORGAN-HILL; HOUSING; PROGRAM; DELAY  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  A self-help housing program where buyers substitute labor for their downpayment could be delayed unless more applicants are found, according to KathyEbright-Robinson of the Housing Authority of Santa Clara County.;    Whilebuyers -- and back-up buyers -- were screened before they were selected bylottery for the 16 &quot;sweat-equity&quot; homes in Morgan Hill, it appears thatanother round of screening is eliminating too many potential buyers, saidEbright-Robinson, a housing development officer.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  APPLICANTS SOUGHT FOR 'SWEAT-EQUITY' HOMES  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     If that occurs, the start of construction could be delayed,Ebright-Robinson said, so the housing authority wants to add to its list ofapplicants. People will be added to the list on a first-come, first-servedbasis.;    Applicants must be first-time home buyers, meaning they haven'towned a house in the past three years, and meet guidelines for family size,income, credit rating and job stability. Maximum family income allowed rangesfrom $30,400 for two people to $47,100 for a family of seven.;    Familiesselected for the self-help project will contribute an estimated $18,000 inlabor toward the home's price, which ranges from $175,000 for two-bedroomhomes to $183,000 for three-bedroom houses. The work will done under thedirection of a licensed contractor and will last from 10 months to a year.;   The houses will be part of the San Pedro Gardens subdivision, which also willcontain 20 rental units for low-income families. The entire subdivision willcost about $6.35 million.;    The &quot;sweat-equity&quot; project is the first for thehousing authority, which is involved in the rental of 9,000 dwellings in thecounty. In addition to the more than 8,000 units it administers for thefederal Department of Housing and Urban Development, the agency manages 250units owned by private parties and 550 units it built for the elderly.;    Thehousing authority, which likes to have three applicants for each unit, hadonly 29 potential buyers for the self-help project, Ebright-Robinson said. Shesaid the March 30 drawing to select buyers was held in an effort to meetrequirements of the California Housing Finance Agency, which providesmortgages for the homes.; IFYOU'RE INTERESTED; People who would like toparticipate in the self-help housing project may pick up an applicationbetween 9 a.m. and 5 p.m. Monday through Friday at 505 W. Julian St., SanJose, or call 993-3050, extension 1090.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  DALE RODEBAUGH, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  South County  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910522  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  May  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  399  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday May 22, 199100143177,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>